🔹 Python Queue Example — Simple Sliding Window with Queue
from collections import deque

window_size = 5
queue = deque()
transactions = [100, 120, 5000, 200, 210, 15000]

for txn in transactions:
    queue.append(txn)
    if len(queue) > window_size:
        queue.popleft()
    print(f"Current window: {list(queue)}, Sum: {sum(queue)}")

GS-Level Insight:

Use deque for O(1) insert/delete operations
Supports real-time aggregation for ML features
Demonstrates understanding of memory-efficient streaming computation
3️⃣ Production — Real-Time Data Handling
🔹 Key Considerations:
Latency
Keep ML inference sub-10ms for high-frequency trading
Use pre-loaded models, async processing, caching
Fault Tolerance
Kafka handles message durability and consumer failover
Dead-letter queues store unprocessable messages
Monitoring
Track throughput, consumer lag, error rate
Ensure ML predictions are timely for downstream systems
Scaling
Partition topics for parallel consumers
Horizontal scaling of ML services for high volume
🔹 Scenario-Based Questions — GS-Level
Scenario	How to Answer
“Transactions are arriving at 10k/sec. ML API cannot keep up.”	Use Kafka topic partitions to parallelize consumers. Pre-load models in memory. Use batch inference if acceptable. Consider async processing.
“ML model crashes on one transaction.”	Use try-except, log failed transaction, send to dead-letter queue, continue processing. Commit offset only after success.
“Kafka consumer lag is increasing.”	Check processing bottleneck, scale consumer instances, optimize ML model for latency, monitor topic partitions and load.
“Queue overflow or slow downstream service.”	Implement backpressure, batch processing, or temporary buffering with queue/deque.
